response: {"request_id":"c778e2c4-15f5-428b-89ba-ed3d4a1de9f8","response":"# Docker & Kubernetes (K8s) Explained\n\n---\n\n## 🐳 Docker\n\n### What is Docker?\nDocker is a **containerization platform** that packages your application and all its dependencies into a **container** — a lightweight, portable, isolated unit.\n\n### Key Concepts\n\n| Concept | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Image** | A blueprint/template for a container (like a class) |\n| **Container** | A running instance of an image (like an object) |\n| **Dockerfile** | Script with instructions to build an image |\n| **Docker Hub** | Registry to store/share images |\n| **Volume** | Persistent storage for containers |\n| **Network** | Communication between containers |\n\n### Simple Dockerfile Example\n```dockerfile\n# Base image\nFROM node:18\n\n# Set working directory\nWORKDIR /app\n\n# Copy and install dependencies\nCOPY package.json .\nRUN npm install\n\n# Copy source code\nCOPY . .\n\n# Expose port\nEXPOSE 3000\n\n# Start command\nCMD [\"node\", \"server.js\"]\n```\n\n### Common Docker Commands\n```bash\ndocker build -t my-app .        # Build image\ndocker run -p 3000:3000 my-app  # Run container\ndocker ps                        # List running containers\ndocker stop <container-id>       # Stop container\ndocker pull nginx                # Pull image from hub\ndocker-compose up                # Run multi-container app\n```\n\n### Why Docker?\n- ✅ **\"Works on my machine\"** problem solved\n- ✅ Consistent environments (dev, staging, prod)\n- ✅ Fast startup vs Virtual Machines\n- ✅ Lightweight & portable\n\n---\n\n## ☸️ Kubernetes (K8s)\n\n### What is Kubernetes?\nKubernetes is a **container orchestration platform** that automates deployment, scaling, and management of containers **at scale**.\n\n> **Analogy:** Docker = shipping container | Kubernetes = the shipping port that manages thousands of containers\n\n### Key Concepts\n\n| Concept | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Pod** | Smallest unit — wraps one or more containers |\n| **Node** | A physical/virtual machine running pods |\n| **Cluster** | Group of nodes managed by K8s |\n| **Deployment** | Manages pod replicas & updates |\n| **Service** | Exposes pods to network traffic |\n| **Namespace** | Virtual cluster for isolation |\n| **ConfigMap** | Store config/env variables |\n| **Secret** | Store sensitive data |\n| **Ingress** | Manages external HTTP access |\n\n### K8s Architecture\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────┐\n│           CONTROL PLANE             │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐ │\n│  │API Server│  │  Scheduler       │ │\n│  └──────────┘  └──────────────────┘ │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐ │\n│  │  etcd    │  │Controller Manager│ │\n│  └──────────┘  └──────────────────┘ │\n└─────────────────────────────────────┘\n         │\n┌────────┴────────────────────┐\n│         WORKER NODES        │\n│  ┌──────────────────────┐   │\n│  │  Node 1              │   │\n│  │  [Pod] [Pod] [Pod]   │   │\n│  └──────────────────────┘   │\n│  ┌──────────────────────┐   │\n│  │  Node 2              │   │\n│  │  [Pod] [Pod]         │   │\n│  └──────────────────────┘   │\n└─────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Simple K8s YAML Examples\n\n**Deployment:**\n```yaml\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: my-app\nspec:\n  replicas: 3          # Run 3 copies\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: my-app\n  template:\n    metadata:\n      labels:\n        app: my-app","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","input_tokens":22,"output_tokens":1024,"latency_ms":14918.72}